post_text:
Today is a much different beginning to our school year! Everyone has worked tirelessly to prepare for this day. We want to thank all of our employees for all the extra work that has gone into preparing for today.

Parents/Guardians/Caregivers, we understand that you are taking on challenges too. There will be connectivity issues, problems with devices, frustrations with making students take virtual learning seriously, and many other things. We will work through those things together.

For all of us, it is no longer about us. It is about doing all we can to make this situation the best it can be for our students. We vow to do all we can to overcome the challenges we are presented.

To our students:

We love you, and while this is not the way we wanted to kick off the school year, we vow to do whatever it takes to help help you virtually until we welcome you back into the school.

Letâ€™s make 2020-2021 the best we can by all working together!

Announcement for Remote Learners:

According to the survey that was completed by parents/guardians, we have homes that do not have access to the Internet.

Students in these homes will be provided offline content as needed, but we have also made our wireless Internet available in our school parking lots so that parents/guardians have a well lit area if they would like to bring their student(s) to gain Internet access after hours. There will also be an announcement made soon of other locations where public WiFi will be available.

post_text:
To the Class of 2020:

None of us would have ever written a script that had your high school careers end the way this one did. Even if we had, we could not have written it to appropriately describe how you have handled it. You have handled these circumstances with class and integrity.

As a school division, we could not be more proud. We certainly wish things could have been much different, but we hope your time with Wise County Schools has prepared you for the future. We wish you nothing short of the best that life has to offer because you will certainly have a story to tell!

To our schools, parents/guardians, and communities, we thank you for doing your best to help our students experience the final events of their time in high school.

Parents:

Schools have been reaching out to parents/guardians confirming their choice between the hybrid model or online model for the 2020-2021 school year.

We are requesting that all parents/guardians that have not spoken with their child(ren)'s teacher or other school staff to please call the school your child(ren) attend and inform them of your choice. Please do this by August 7, 2020.

Our schools will accept changes to this decision until August 13, 2020, so that we have a week to prepare for the first day of school.

Thank you!

Tots On Target
June 29 at 6:41 PM Â·

***Tape Pull Activity***

This super simple and super fun activity targets so many important developmental skills.....another win for painterâ€™s tape!!!

1. Visual Perception â€” figuring out which piece of tape to pull off first

2. Fine Motor â€” using the hand/finger muscles to peel the ends of the tape

3. Gross Motor â€” doing the activity on a vertical surface to strengthen the neck and shoulder muscles

4. Crossing Midline â€” By using one hand, the child is forced to cross the imaginary vertical line running down the middle of his body

post_text:
The data for P-EBT was sent to Va Dept of Soc Services on May 8. This process may take 4 â€“ 6
weeks, and not all households will receive the benefit at the same time.

How do I know if I am eligible?
Schools will provide information for all eligible students directly to VDSS. Households do not have to apply for P-EBT. If you believe there are eligible students in your household but
you do not receive P-EBT by the middle of June, call (804) 726-7000.

When will P-EBT benefits be available?
If your family is currently receiving SNAP benefits and you are eligible for P-EBT, additional benefits will be added to your EBT card in the next two weeks. If your family is
not receiving SNAP, you will receive a P-EBT card in the mail in the next four to six weeks.

People living in the same area with children who attend the same schools may not receive benefits at the same time. Eligible households will receive benefits for the entire period their students were eligible, even if they do not receive benefits until the end of May or June.

Attention Students of Central High School, Eastside High School, and L.F. Addington Middle School

We would like to make you aware that Free and Reduced Meal Applications can be completed now. If your household situation has changed and you wish to complete a free and reduced meal application, please go to the schoolâ€™s webpage or the Wise County Schoolâ€™s webpage (www.wisek12.org) to print off the meal application and complete it. Please note applications must be signed.

Paper applications are available at the central office and at LFA, EHS, and CHS. The central office and schools will be open on Tuesday and Wednesday to pick up and submit paper applications. If you submit a completed application to the school your child attends or to the central office by Wednesday, 5/6 at 12:00 noon and the application is processed as free or reduced price eligible, you may qualify for P-EBT benefits.

If you have questions, please call Brandi Bates at 328-8017.
Applications may also be emailed to bbates@wisek12.org or faxed to the central office at 328-3350.

Paper applications are available at the central office and at LFA, EHS, and CHS. The central office and schools will be open on Tuesday and Wednesday to pick up and submit paper applications. If you submit a completed application to the school your child attends or to the central office by Wednesday, 5/6 at 12:00 noon and the application is processed as free or reduced price eligible, you may qualify for P-EBT benefits.

If you have questions, please call Brandi Bates at 328-8017.
Applications may also be emailed to bbates@wisek12.org or faxed to the central office at 328-3350.

UPDATED MEAL SERVICE INFORMATION - CHANGE IN MEAL SERVICE

Wise County Public Schools will continue meal service during school closure. In consideration of the Governorâ€™s issuance of a Stay at Home Order and to assist our community and staff members minimize contact, starting Wednesday April 8, meals will be provided one day per week. Five breakfasts and five lunches will be provided for each child on Wednesday each week.

Meals will be available for drive through pick up from 11:00am â€“ 1:00pm at the following locations:
Coeburn Primary, J.W. Adams Combined, St. Paul Elementary, Union Primary, and Wise Primary

Meals will also be available on bus routes in each community. Bus runs will start at 11:00am on Wednesdays.

We strongly encourage social distancing and minimal contact during drive thru pick up and delivery.

If you have questions, please call Brandi Bates, Director of Food Services, at (276) 328-8017 or the school in your community providing meals.

In regards to SOLs, the federal government has informed states that they will receive waivers for testing. In Virginia, this still requires some action by the general assembly. We will also provide updates on that as they are made available, but are confident news will be forthcoming.

UPDATED INFORMATION REGARDING MEAL PROGRAM:

Wise County Public Schools will be providing meals at no cost (breakfast and lunch) to all children 18 and under (or through 21 if enrolled in WCPS) beginning Wednesday, March 18.

Children MUST be present at the bus stop or at pick up to receive the meals.

Mondayâ€™s bag will include breakfast and lunch for 2 days and Wednesdayâ€™s bag will include breakfast and lunch for 3 days.

Meals will be available for pick up Monday and Wednesday from 11:00-1:00 at the following locations: Coeburn Primary, J.W. Adams Combined, St. Paul Elementary, Union Primary, and Wise Primary. By request meals are also available on bus routes. Bus runs will start at 11:00 am on Mondays and Wednesdays beginning Wednesday, March 18. Parents will be called the first day of delivery to let families know approximate arrival times.

These meals will be provided during this 2 week school closure with intentions to continue if schools have extended closures. If you have any questions please call Brandi Bates at (276) 328-8017 or your local school.

Wise County Public Schools will be providing developmental and speech/language screenings for preschool children between ages 2-5. Screenings will take place in the Early Childhood Special Education office at the Career Technical Center in Wise on the first Friday of each month between 9:00-10:00 AM. You may call 321-8144 for more information or to schedule an appointment.

Our next scheduled screening date is Friday, March 6th. In case of a delay or closing we will reschedule and post a new date.

**Please note that all Pre-K students and Head Start students participate in developmental screenings as part of those programs. Many children in local daycares also participated in our fall screenings with parent permission.**

So excited to share pics. of our Tuesday S.T.E.A.M. group Mentor Meeting. Some of our 6th and 7th grade students have been matched up with Dominion employees, who will serve as mentors for the next year in this pilot program designed to promote the development of positive self-esteem and social competence, academic achievement, and the avoidance of high risk behaviors. So thankful for this community partnership with Dominion! The students had a blast and are looking forward to next week!

Wise Primary School Family Engagement
November 21, 2019 at 5:43 PM Â·

The Title I Reading classes at Wise Primary School celebrated the power of reading this week and participated in Read for the Record. Each class read Thank You, Omu! written by Oge Mora. In the story, Omu made a large pot of thick red stew for her evening meal. Everyone in Omuâ€™s neighborhood smelled the delicious stew and one by one they followed their noses toward the scrumptious scent. Omu shared her stew with each person and then had no stew left for her evening meal. At the end of the story, Omuâ€™s neighbors and community come back to give dinner to Omu. This was a wonderful story in teaching our students the importance of sharing and the importance of a community coming together to show love and gratitude.

The students had fun making thank you cards for our wonderful cafeteria ladies who prepare our breakfast and lunch each day. Ms. Phillips, Mrs. Taylor and Mrs. Balthis also shared yummy soup with their Title I Reading students.

Union Primary's "Spooky Science Night" was amazing! A big shout out to all our community volunteers who came and set up their awesome stations for our students. There were so many smiles on our students's faces as they were engaged in all the math/science activities. UVA at Wise did a fantastic job setting the stage for our event at the beginning with their "Blast "Off' before the students ventured through the building to find more spectacular math/science demos set up by our community helpers. We could not have done this without them! Again , much appreciation for everyone who made this event a memorable experience for every student and family that came. Get ready for an overload of pictures! More to come soon.

August 16, 2019 at 4:21 PM Â·

The Wise County Career-Technical Center is pleased to announce our first two students to sign up for the statewide youth apprenticeship program: EHS/CTC student Austin Thad Funk and UHS/CTC student Nicholas Hayden. Both students will be working youth apprenticeships with Buchanan Electric under the guidance of Electricity/HVAC teacher Joe Buchanan, earning high school credit, work experience, and wages at the same time. Interested businesses may contact the Wise County Career-Technical Center at 276-328-6113.

post_text: We have some amazing people out there that do extraordinary things! Please share this so that anyone in need of this information may receive it. Thank you!
shared_text:
Mary Beth Masters
June 3, 2019 at 2:48 AM Â·

If you have a school-aged child in need of breakfast and lunch this summer, simply text â€œFOODâ€ to 877877, enter your zip code, and receive a message back with a location closest to where they can get free summer meals.

Summer is the time of greatest need/deficiency for food insecure youth given there is lesser access to food/nutrition programs (school breakfasts, lunches, etc.) than during the school year.

Please copy, paste, and post. Even if you aren't in need, someone else's kids might be. No child deserves to go hungry, ever.

post_text: Thank you, American Legion Post 243, for your support!
shared_text:
American Legion Post 243 is with Grant Kilgore.
May 22, 2019 at 3:52 PM Â·

American Legion Post 243 Norton, VA recently donated backpacks to Norton Elementary Schools, Wise County Schools and the Wise County Christian School. Pictured below is Melissa Kiser (Counselor) accepting on behalf of Norton, Mark Giles (Director) accepting on behalf of Wise County Schools and Missy Bentley (Pre-School Teacher) accepting on behalf of Wise Christian School. Also pictured are Post Commander Tom Bates, Judge Advocate Grant Kilgore and Finance Officer Bill Stapleton.
